# Backend Rules (NestJS / apps/api)

## Module Structure

Follow NestJS domain module conventions. Each domain owns its controller, service, module, and DTOs:

```
src/
  employees/
    employees.controller.ts
    employees.service.ts
    employees.module.ts
    dto/
      create-employee.dto.ts
```

Do not put business logic in controllers. Controllers handle HTTP concerns only; delegate everything else to services.

## Schema and Migrations

- **Never** modify `prisma/schema.prisma` or create migrations without explicit instruction.
- After any schema change is approved, run `npm run db:generate` before using the new types.

## Error Logging

Log errors with enough context to diagnose in production, but never log secrets or raw passwords.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD
this.logger.error('Failed to create session', {
  employeeId,
  error: err.message,
});

// ❌ BAD — no context
this.logger.error(err);

// ❌ BAD — logs sensitive data
this.logger.debug({ body: request.body }); // body may contain passwords
```

Use NestJS `Logger` (`new Logger(ClassName.name)`) — do not use `console.log` in production code.

## Explicit Dependencies

- Inject dependencies via the constructor; do not import singletons directly.
- Do not cause side effects in a service that the caller cannot observe or control.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD — caller controls the event emitter
constructor(private readonly eventEmitter: EventEmitter2) {}

// ❌ BAD — hidden coupling
import { globalEventBus } from '../shared/global-bus';
```

## DTOs and Validation

- Use `class-validator` decorators on all incoming DTOs.
- Reuse types from `@repo/contracts` for response shapes when they exist.
